title: Tree Arithmetic with Phylogenetic Flows
text: start kappa transformation simplest one perspective phylogenetic flow. simply raising branch lengths phylogenetic tree power (kappa parameter). Typically, kappa values less one used, values greater one also possible. Kappa values less one tend ‘shrink’ branch lengths non-linearly towards 1, kappa = 0, branch lengths exactly one. sometimes used model ‘speciational’ change along branches, model weighted branch lengths insensitive branch length, branching structure . First start generating random tree using ape, converting pfc. demonstrate transformation.  create pfc object phylo object, branch lengths tree automatically used phylogenetic flow feature. can easily perform kappa transformation directly raising pfc object desired kappa parameter. Let’s test kappa = 0.5  can see result transformation longer branches become relatively shorter compared branches started shorter. can series transformation see tree converges kappa = 0.  Pagel’s lambda delta transformations little complicated still pretty easy calculate phyf.
code: set.seed(3445564) tree <- rcoal(100) tree_pfc <- pf_as_pfc(tree) plot(tree_pfc) tree_pfc_0.5 <- tree_pfc^0.5 plot(tree_pfc_0.5) with_par(list(mfrow = c(3, 3), mar = c(2, 2, 1, 1), xpd = NA), {   for(i in seq(1, 0, length.out = 9)) plot(tree_pfc^i, main = sprintf("kappa = %s", i), show.tip.label = FALSE) })

title: Tree Arithmetic with Phylogenetic Flows
text: Pagel’s lambda transformation multiplies internal branch lengths constant (lambda parameter), whilst compensatorily growing terminal branches keep total distances root tips . , lambda usually set less 1, lambda goes zero internal branches shrink nothing, leaving terminla branches. model derived transforming phylogenetic variance-covariance matrix implied phylogeny. Lambda > 1 usually used resulting variance-covariance matrix can become ill-conditioned. perspective branch length transformation multiply internal branch two much greater zero, height can become greater height tips, maintain total distance root tips without negative branch lengths! transformation phyf need two transformations, one internal branches one external branches. also need information root tips lengths, sum phylogenetic flow feature.  ## Pagel’s Delta Lastly, Pagel’s delta transformation transformation node heights phylogeny, raising power delta parameter. effect shrinking branches near tips near root. context model evolution tree, used model ‘slow-’ evolution time. can acheive transformation first generating pfc node heights phylogenetic flow features instead branch lengths. Node heights can calculated cumulative sum branch lengths phylogenetic flow. phyf pf_flow_cumsum() function .  Now get back branch lengths instead node heights need subtract node height node height immediate ancestor. phyf also convenient function : pf_anc(), returns pfc feature replaces feature value ancestor.  series deltas:
code: lambda <- 0.5 lambda_pfc <- tree_pfc root2node_lens <- pf_flow_sum(lambda_pfc) pf_internal(lambda_pfc) <- pf_internal(lambda_pfc) * lambda pf_terminal(lambda_pfc) <- pf_terminal(lambda_pfc) + (root2node_lens - pf_flow_sum(lambda_pfc)) plot(lambda_pfc, show.tip.label = FALSE) lambda_trans <- function(x, lambda = 0.5) {   root2node_lens <- pf_flow_sum(x)   pf_internal(x) <- pf_internal(x) * lambda   pf_terminal(x) <- pf_terminal(x) + (root2node_lens - pf_flow_sum(x))   x } with_par(list(mfrow = c(3, 3), mar = c(2, 2, 1, 1), xpd = NA), {   for(i in seq(1, 0, length.out = 9)) plot(lambda_trans(tree_pfc, i), type = "f", main = sprintf("lambda = %s", i), show.tip.label = FALSE) }) node_heights <- pf_flow_cumsum(tree_pfc) head(node_heights) #> <pfc<e:198>[6]> #> First  6 phylogenetic flows:  #> [1] ◎──  1.2──→ Node3 ──  1.2──→ Node4 ──  1.8──→ t24  #>  #> [2] ◎──  1.2──→ Node3 ──  1.2──→ Node4 ──  1.6──→ Node10 ──  1.6──→ Node11 ──  1.7──→ Node23 ──  1.7──→ Node46 ──  1.8──→ t13  #>  #> [3] ◎──  1.2──→ Node3 ──  1.2──→ Node4 ──  1.6──→ Node10 ──  1.6──→ Node11 ──  1.7──→ Node23 ──  1.7──→ Node46 ──  1.8──→ Node58 ──  1.8──→ t7  #>  #> [4] ◎──  1.2──→ Node3 ──  1.2──→ Node4 ──  1.6──→ Node10 ──  1.6──→ Node11 ──  1.7──→ Node23 ──  1.7──→ Node46 ──  1.8──→ Node58 ──  1.8──→ t40  #>  #> [5] ◎──  1.2──→ Node3 ──  1.2──→ Node4 ──  1.6──→ Node10 ──  1.6──→ Node11 ──  1.7──→ Node23 ──  1.7──→ Node39 ──  1.8──→ t48  #>  #> [6] ◎──  1.2──→ Node3 ──  1.2──→ Node4 ──  1.6──→ Node10 ──  1.6──→ Node11 ──  1.7──→ Node23 ──  1.7──→ Node39 ──  1.8──→ t81 plot(node_heights) delta <- 0.4 new_pfc <- node_heights^delta head(pf_anc(new_pfc)) #> <pfc<e:198>[6]> #> First  6 phylogenetic flows:  #> [1] ◎──  0.0──→ Node3 ──  1.1──→ Node4 ──  1.1──→ t24  #>  #> [2] ◎──  0.0──→ Node3 ──  1.1──→ Node4 ──  1.1──→ Node10 ──  1.2──→ Node11 ──  1.2──→ Node23 ──  1.2──→ Node46 ──  1.2──→ t13  #>  #> [3] ◎──  0.0──→ Node3 ──  1.1──→ Node4 ──  1.1──→ Node10 ──  1.2──→ Node11 ──  1.2──→ Node23 ──  1.2──→ Node46 ──  1.2──→ Node58 ──  1.3──→ t7  #>  #> [4] ◎──  0.0──→ Node3 ──  1.1──→ Node4 ──  1.1──→ Node10 ──  1.2──→ Node11 ──  1.2──→ Node23 ──  1.2──→ Node46 ──  1.2──→ Node58 ──  1.3──→ t40  #>  #> [5] ◎──  0.0──→ Node3 ──  1.1──→ Node4 ──  1.1──→ Node10 ──  1.2──→ Node11 ──  1.2──→ Node23 ──  1.2──→ Node39 ──  1.2──→ t48  #>  #> [6] ◎──  0.0──→ Node3 ──  1.1──→ Node4 ──  1.1──→ Node10 ──  1.2──→ Node11 ──  1.2──→ Node23 ──  1.2──→ Node39 ──  1.2──→ t81 new_pfc <- new_pfc - pf_anc(new_pfc) plot(new_pfc) delta_trans <- function(x, delta = 0.5) {   new_pfc <- pf_flow_cumsum(tree_pfc)^delta   new_pfc <- new_pfc - pf_anc(new_pfc)   new_pfc } with_par(list(mfrow = c(3, 3), mar = c(2, 2, 1, 1), xpd = NA), {   for(i in seq(0.5, 4, length.out = 9)) plot(delta_trans(tree_pfc, i), type = "f", main = sprintf("delta = %s", i), show.tip.label = FALSE) })

title: Phylogenetic Flow Objects for Easy Manipulation and Modelling of Data on Phylogenetic Trees and Graphs
text: goal phyf implement tibble subclass useful statistical modelling phylogenetic trees. mainly implements phylogenetic flow (pf) object essentially tibble one phylogenetic flow collection (pfc) columns. Phylogenetic flow collection columns collections phylogenetic flow paths (pfp) phylogenetic flow features (pff), store data information flows phylogeny root node (phylogenies must rooted work phyf) tips (internal nodes). allows easy manipulation phylogeny associated data. objects used package fibre phylogenetic branch regression models, highly felxible framework comparative analysis modelling trait evolution across phylogeny.

Usually data tips, joining pf object (using e.g. dplyr::left_join()) internal node rows recieve NA values. desired behaviour. missing values easy drop fitting model, useful later making predictions (, ancestral state estimates).
